✅ Approved the contribution.
Comment: Funny puzzle, nice for a clash of code !

Any specific reason to have it on 'Shortest' mode only? I think fastest would also be fine. I'm happy to approve, just double-checking whether you intended this to be shortest-only or that it is by accident.

NB: I had fun trying it as shortest.

print((a*10+b)*(10**c))

Comment: Good clash, love the idea! Errors raised have been addressed, so as stated I approve.

Nice one @Boulib.
Code-Parser

✅ Approved the contribution.
Comment: Why didn't I think of that?

Good Clash, and nice concept!

This clash involves dictionaries, a few simple calculations and outputting an integer.
It is quite simple to solve once you understand these topics... even to a basic level.

Frankly, I like the idea and the execution of this concept... for now I will only upvote this contribution. Once I see that the issues raised by @5DN1L are addressed via comment or reply, I will consider approving... provided that there are no follow-ups or new issues raised.

Nice work anyways, @Boulib.
Code-Parser

Input
* Please rewrite as:
<<Line 1>>: 3 space-separated strings for 3 resistor colors.

Output
* Please change "Line 1 :" to "<<Line 1>>:".

Stub generator
* Please change "read colors:string(100)" to "read color1:word(10) color2:word(10) color3:word(10)".

Cases
* Please add tests where Purple, Grey and White are covered.

* Please add validators where Black, Grey and White are covered.

Thanks.
a bit late but what do the letters mean?

Instead of looking for the whole color name, I look for the final two letters of each color (.find(p[-2:])). That will give me 0 for (bla)ck, 2 for (bro)wn, etcetera,, which with //2 turn in 0, 1, etcetera. I found out the two final letters are distinctive for each of the colors.
wow thats a really smart approach. wish i would've found that when i was doing this coc.. :)
